                <!-- Teaching Tips -->
                <div class="educator-section">
                    <h3>💡 Teaching Tips by Lesson</h3>
                    <div class="tip-grid">
                        <div class="tip-card purple">
                            <h4>L1: Probability</h4>
                            <p>Use physical manipulatives (coins, dice, marbles) before abstract formulas. Let students discover empirical probability converges to theoretical.</p>
                            <div class="strategy"><strong>Activity:</strong> Have students flip coins 50 times and compare to P(H) = 0.5</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="tip-card green">
                            <h4>L2: Counting</h4>
                            <p>Always start with small examples students can list by hand. Then show how formulas save time for larger problems.</p>
                            <div class="strategy"><strong>Activity:</strong> "How many 2-letter codes from ABC?" List them, then show 3×3=9</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="tip-card pink">
                            <h4>L3: Data Organization</h4>
                            <p>Use data students care about (class birthdays, favorite foods). Personal connection increases engagement.</p>
                            <div class="strategy"><strong>Activity:</strong> Survey the class and build graphs together in real-time</div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Common Misconceptions -->
                <div class="educator-section">
                    <h3>⚠️ Common Pitfalls & Error Analysis</h3>
                    
                    <div class="misconception-card">
                        <div class="error">❌ "Permutation and combination give the same answer"</div>
                        <div class="explanation">Students often confuse when order matters. They may calculate C(5,3) when they should use P(5,3) for race placements.</div>
                        <div class="correction">
                            <strong>Teaching Fix:</strong> Use the "ice cream cone vs. bowl" analogy. Cone = order matters (vanilla on top is different from chocolate on top). Bowl = order doesn't matter (same scoops either way).
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="misconception-card">
                        <div class="error">❌ "Histogram bars can have gaps"</div>
                        <div class="explanation">Students draw histograms like bar graphs because they look similar.</div>
                        <div class="correction">
                            <strong>Teaching Fix:</strong> Emphasize "Touch = Together" for continuous data. Ask: "Can someone score 79.5? Yes! Data flows continuously, so bars flow together."
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="misconception-card">
                        <div class="error">❌ "Independent events can't happen together"</div>
                        <div class="explanation">Students confuse "independent" with "mutually exclusive."</div>
                        <div class="correction">
                            <strong>Teaching Fix:</strong> Independent = one doesn't AFFECT the other. Mutually exclusive = one PREVENTS the other. Flipping heads doesn't prevent rolling a 6!
                        </div>
